                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d859">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/12727.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Saltillo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-03T12:00:00-06:41">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 3, 1914, noon</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>At the preliminary meeting yesterday the [Carbajal] envoys manifested surprise
                    that they were expected to make an unconditional surrender.<note n="57"
                        xml:id="d859fn57">See inclosure with Mr. Silliman’s last despatch of July
                        31.</note> When advised that nothing else had ever been contemplated they
                    requested permission to consult their Government by telegraph, which was
                    granted. Pending reply no further meeting is announced and no suspension of
                    military operations has been ordered.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Silliman</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
